description.text: A replacement for the stock belt clap that includes a tensioning screw. This works in a similar way to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10274 but to maintain straight belt travel the belt is clamped at the bottom and free at the top. The SCAD file is parametric so this should be adaptable to other machines and belt sizes. **Version 2 makes the corners round, adds a slimmer clamping strap and incorporates Aggressive's impovement to the nipple form.

1) Print and clean up
2) Slide an M4 nut into the slot down the parts middle
3) Insert the M4 tensioning screw chose a 30mm or bigger cap screw so you have enogh thread to tension the belt effectivly.
4) Put the nipple on the end of the temsioning screw
5) Mount on the Y frog as usual but instead of clamping the belt between the 2 plastic parts loop the bet over the tension screw and under the bottom of the clamp.
6) Leave the clamp loose until you wish to tension the belt, with the tension screw mid travel rougly tension the belt and then tighten the fixing screws.
7) Add or remove tension by the tensioning srcew (clockwise turns tension the belt) I have marked this a work in progress until I have my machine working

description.text:
DM: In the front yard is a classically designed well with a bucket and hand crank. As you look down into the well you see that is is dried up and that at the bottom is a shiny long sword with a jeweled hilt.

Player: I check the rope and crank mechanism to make sure it is in good condition, and if it is the others can lower me down into the well to get the sword.

DM: The rope and crank look strong and you see no sign of rot or excessive wear. The well is narrow, and you have to stand on the bucket and keep your elbows tucked in in order to be lowered down.

Other players: we lower him slowly looking for bad spots on the rope and problems with the winch as we go.

DM: About 3/4 the way down you begin feel a vibration in the ground.

Other Players: we start pulling him up!

DM: you get him about 20 feet from the top. when suddenly you see a dark grey shark like shape, seemingly swimming trough the dirt, burst from one side of the well, bite the rope, and disappear into the other side. With the rope cut you fall to the bottom of the well where you are pummeled by rocks and dirt left in the wake of the beast. You take 6 points of falling damage and you are barely able to move due to the confined space. Then you begin to hear the vibration again. It is coming back for you.

This is a remix of mz4250's work on shapeways.

title: Tunnelsystem fuer Kaninchen; tunnel system for rabbits

description.text:
Zur Verwendung mit 160mm Rohren aus dem Baumarkt.
Damit können mehrere Kaninchenställe sicher verbunden werden. Auch zum schnellen Auf- und Abbau geeignet.
Der Auslass, zum Einbau in die Stallwandung, hat ein Außengewinde. Auf das Gewinde kann ein Deckel zum sicheren Verschließen der Öffnung geschraubt werden.
Der Innendurchmesser beträgt ca. 162mm, damit die Rohre verschiebbar sind. Die Auslässe sollten deshalb nicht scaliert werden. Somit muss der Deckel (Deckel-Gewinde.stl) etwas größer im Durchmesser gedruckt werden (z.B. 102% auf x und y im Slicer) damit das Gewinde läuft.
Zum Testen habe ich zwei Testdateien für das Gewinde erstellt.

Die Rohrstützen sind ebenfalls mit Gewinde versehen und somit verstellbar.
Das obere Teil der Stütze ist zum einfacheren Druck zweiteilig und muss zusammengeklebt werden. Der Gabelteil (Staender_oben_ohne.stl sollte liegend gedruckt werden. Dann wird die Gabel stabieler und es wird nur wenig Support benötigt.

Bei der Stütze muss das untere Teil (Staender_unten_gr.stl) etwas kleiner gedruckt werden (z.B. 98% auf x und y im Slicer).

To use with tubes with 160mm Diameter (in Germany available at "Homedepot" like stores).
You can connect several rabbit staples or you can use the system to let your rabbits out on the lawn in a safe way.
The outlet has a thread. You can print a cover, also with a thread, for closing the outlet, when it's not needed.
For an properly working thread, you have to print the cover a little bit bigger in the Diameter (f.e. 102% on x and y in the slicer).
There are two testfiles for the outlet thread.

The supports for the tubes also have a thread.
The upper part of the tube support are two parts. You have to glue them together. Print the most upper part (Staender_oben_ohne.stl) in lying Position.

Print the lower part of the tube Support (Staender_unten_gr.stl) a Little bit smaller in the Diameter (f.e. 98% on x and y in the slicer). Attention: Don't reduce the hight, because the thread will be squeezed and then don't work properly)

description.text:
This is a variable length and ring AR printable form of a chainmaille weave coined Power Line.
More information on the weave itself can be found here:
http://www.mailleartisans.org/weaves/weavedisplay.php?key=629

Open in customizer to generate your stl file for printing.
Sometimes the customizer does not launch correctly. If this is the case, follow this link: http://www.thingiverse.com/apps/customizer This weave can be woven at a smaller aspect ratio than what can mathematically be represented. The orbital connection on each side of the unit can only be achieved mathematically above and AR of 5.46 (let alone bent in this weave). However, very slight non-circular aspects of the ring do allow this to be woven with standard metal rings at a lower AR.
More info on this interaction can be found in the discussion in this forum thread: http://www.mailleartisans.org/board/viewtopic.php?t=17527&postdays=0&postorder=asc&start=15#223806

Project: Plumb Line Bob

A plumb line has been used since ancient times, and it still remains an essential tool for building physical objects all over the world.
The design of plumb bob has changed from a simple stone hanging on a string to a pointed, more accurate and stable design.

This project aims on printing a quintessential tool for a maker and motivate children on learning more about hand tools used in building physical objects.

HOW TO USE:
Just push a piece of thread through the cap, and tie it to the bars on the inside of the cap.
After this is done just push the cap through the hole on the top of the body and twist to lock it in place.
Now this string is ready to be hung on any nail, or pin. The string once stable, will be a straight line perpendicular to the ground regardless of the regularity of surfaces.

These boxes, designed to store the EasyLink+ and Inspiro, were created for the 2014 Idea Challenge, organized by @Whampus. The challenge paired special education teachers with 3-D modelers to create unique assistive technology solutions to unusual problems at their school or in their district. One particular teacher had this idea:

"My idea would help with the organization and storage of equipment that is used by students with hearing loss. We provide FM equipment to approximately 200 students in 13 districts, so we have a large inventory of equipment to organize. The FM systems are used by students in schools to help improve their auditory access to instruction (in other words, it amplifies sound to help them hear their teachers better). Many of the pieces of equipment are small enough to be organized within plastic craft organizers, but we would like to improve our storage of the FM microphones/transmitters.

Basically, it's a drawer divider that would be a custom size to hold the transmitter units. We currently use very old foam that was used for shipping some equipment that we no longer use, but it has helped us store the pieces more securely than just having to put them all together in one drawer."

I designed these 3-D printable boxes as a solution to this problem. They can fit neatly together in a drawer in various configurations maximizing storage space and minimizing the ability for the individual storage slots to slide around. They provide easy access to the equipment and its cables and wires inside.
